Note: Cron Scheduling Module
Note: Provides comprehensive cron expression parsing, scheduling, and execution timing
Note: with support for advanced cron features, timezone handling, and next execution calculations.

Import "datetime/datetime" as datetime_module
Import "datetime/time" as time_module
Import "datetime/timezone" as timezone_module
Import "collections/list" as list_utils

Note: Cron Types

Type CronExpression is Dictionary with:
    minute as String
    hour as String
    day_of_month as String
    month as String
    day_of_week as String
    year as Optional[String]
    timezone as Optional[timezone_module.Timezone]
    original_expression as String
    parsed_fields as Dictionary[String, Any]
    is_valid as Boolean
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type CronField is Dictionary with:
    field_type as CronFieldType
    values as List[Integer]
    ranges as List[Dictionary[String, Integer]]
    step_value as Optional[Integer]
    special_value as Optional[String]
    raw_expression as String

Type CronFieldType is:
    | MINUTE
    | HOUR
    | DAY_OF_MONTH
    | MONTH
    | DAY_OF_WEEK
    | YEAR

Type CronSchedule is Dictionary with:
    expression as CronExpression
    next_execution as Optional[datetime_module.DateTime]
    previous_execution as Optional[datetime_module.DateTime]
    execution_count as Integer
    is_active as Boolean
    description as Optional[String]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type CronExecution is Dictionary with:
    schedule as CronSchedule
    execution_time as datetime_module.DateTime
    expected_time as datetime_module.DateTime
    delay_milliseconds as Integer
    success as Boolean
    error_message as Optional[String]
    duration_nanoseconds as Integer

Note: Cron Expression Parsing

Process called "parse_cron_expression" that takes expression as String and timezone as Optional[timezone_module.Timezone] returns CronExpression:
    Note: Parse cron expression into structured format
    Try:
        Let trimmed_expr be trim_string with string as expression
        Let parts be split_string with string as trimmed_expr and separator as " "
        
        Note: Validate field count (5 or 6 fields supported)
        If length_of_list with list as parts is less than 5 or length_of_list with list as parts is greater than 6:
            Throw CronError with message as "Invalid cron expression format. Expected 5 or 6 fields, got " plus (length_of_list with list as parts) as string
        
        Let minute_field be parts[0]
        Let hour_field be parts[1]
        Let day_month_field be parts[2]
        Let month_field be parts[3]
        Let day_week_field be parts[4]
        Let year_field be ""
        
        If length_of_list with list as parts is equal to 6:
            Set year_field to parts[5]
        
        Note: Parse each field
        Let parsed_fields be Dictionary with:
            "minute" as parse_cron_field with expression as minute_field and field_type as MINUTE
            "hour" as parse_cron_field with expression as hour_field and field_type as HOUR
            "day_of_month" as parse_cron_field with expression as day_month_field and field_type as DAY_OF_MONTH
            "month" as parse_cron_field with expression as month_field and field_type as MONTH
            "day_of_week" as parse_cron_field with expression as day_week_field and field_type as DAY_OF_WEEK
        
        If year_field is not equal to "":
            Set parsed_fields["year"] to parse_cron_field with expression as year_field and field_type as YEAR
        
        Let final_timezone be timezone or timezone_module.get_utc_timezone
        
        Return CronExpression with:
            minute as minute_field
            hour as hour_field
            day_of_month as day_month_field
            month as month_field
            day_of_week as day_week_field
            year as year_field if year_field is not equal to "" otherwise none
            timezone as final_timezone
            original_expression as expression
            parsed_fields as parsed_fields
            is_valid as true
            metadata as Dictionary with "parsed_at" as datetime_module.now
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Return CronExpression with:
            minute as ""
            hour as ""
            day_of_month as ""
            month as ""
            day_of_week as ""
            year as none
            timezone as none
            original_expression as expression
            parsed_fields as empty dictionary
            is_valid as false
            metadata as Dictionary with "error" as error as string

Process called "parse_cron_field" that takes expression as String and field_type as CronFieldType returns CronField:
    Note: Parse individual cron field (minute, hour, etc.)
    Try:
        Let field_ranges be get_field_ranges with field_type as field_type
        Let min_value be field_ranges["min"]
        Let max_value be field_ranges["max"]
        
        Note: Handle special values
        If expression is equal to "*":
            Return CronField with:
                field_type as field_type
                values as generate_range_list with start as min_value and end as max_value
                ranges as empty list
                step_value as none
                special_value as "*"
                raw_expression as expression
        
        If expression is equal to "?":
            Return CronField with:
                field_type as field_type
                values as empty list
                ranges as empty list
                step_value as none
                special_value as "?"
                raw_expression as expression
        
        Note: Handle step values (*/5, 10-20/2)
        Let step_value be none
        Let base_expression be expression
        
        If "/" in expression:
            Let step_parts be split_string with string as expression and separator as "/"
            Set base_expression to step_parts[0]
            Set step_value to string_to_integer with string as step_parts[1]
        
        Note: Handle ranges and lists
        Let values be empty list
        Let ranges be empty list
        
        If "," in base_expression:
            Note: Handle comma-separated values
            Let value_parts be split_string with string as base_expression and separator as ","
            For each part in value_parts:
                If "-" in part:
                    Let range_result be parse_cron_range with expression as part and min_value as min_value and max_value as max_value
                    Call ranges.append with item as range_result
                    Call extend_list with target as values and source as generate_range_list with start as range_result["start"] and end as range_result["end"]
                Otherwise:
                    Let value be string_to_integer with string as part
                    If value is greater than or equal to min_value and value is less than or equal to max_value:
                        Call values.append with item as value
        Otherwise if "-" in base_expression:
            Note: Handle single range
            Let range_result be parse_cron_range with expression as base_expression and min_value as min_value and max_value as max_value
            Call ranges.append with item as range_result
            Call extend_list with target as values and source as generate_range_list with start as range_result["start"] and end as range_result["end"]
        Otherwise if base_expression is equal to "*":
            Call extend_list with target as values and source as generate_range_list with start as min_value and end as max_value
        Otherwise:
            Note: Handle single value
            Let value be string_to_integer with string as base_expression
            If value is greater than or equal to min_value and value is less than or equal to max_value:
                Call values.append with item as value
        
        Note: Apply step value if present
        If step_value is not none:
            Set values to apply_step_to_values with values as values and step as step_value
        
        Return CronField with:
            field_type as field_type
            values as remove_duplicates with list as values
            ranges as ranges
            step_value as step_value
            special_value as none
            raw_expression as expression
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Throw CronError with message as "Failed to parse cron field '" plus expression plus "': " plus error as string

Process called "validate_cron_expression" that takes expression as CronExpression returns Boolean:
    Note: Validate parsed cron expression for correctness
    Try:
        If not expression.is_valid:
            Return false
        
        Note: Validate each field has valid values
        For each field_name and field_data in expression.parsed_fields:
            Let field as CronField be field_data
            
            If field.special_value is none and field.values size is equal to 0:
                Return false
        
        Note: Validate day of month and day of week aren't both specified (except with ?)
        Let day_month_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["day_of_month"]
        Let day_week_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["day_of_week"]
        
        If day_month_field.special_value is not equal to "?" and day_week_field.special_value is not equal to "?":
            If day_month_field.values size is greater than 0 and day_week_field.values size is greater than 0:
                Note: Both day fields specified - this is valid in cron but can be confusing
                Call log_cron_warning with message as "Both day_of_month and day_of_week specified in cron expression"
        
        Return true
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Return false

Note: Cron Schedule Management

Process called "create_cron_schedule" that takes expression as String and timezone as Optional[timezone_module.Timezone] and description as Optional[String] returns CronSchedule:
    Note: Create a cron schedule from expression
    Try:
        Let cron_expr be parse_cron_expression with expression as expression and timezone as timezone
        
        If not validate_cron_expression with expression as cron_expr:
            Throw CronError with message as "Invalid cron expression: " plus expression
        
        Let schedule be CronSchedule with:
            expression as cron_expr
            next_execution as none
            previous_execution as none
            execution_count as 0
            is_active as true
            description as description
            metadata as Dictionary with "created_at" as datetime_module.now
        
        Note: Calculate initial next execution
        Set schedule.next_execution to calculate_next_execution with schedule as schedule and from_time as datetime_module.now
        
        Return schedule
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Throw CronError with message as "Failed to create cron schedule: " plus error as string

Process called "calculate_next_execution" that takes schedule as CronSchedule and from_time as datetime_module.DateTime returns Optional[datetime_module.DateTime]:
    Note: Calculate next execution time for cron schedule
    Try:
        Let current_time be from_time
        Let expression be schedule.expression
        
        Note: Start from next minute to avoid immediate execution
        Let search_start be datetime_module.add_minutes with datetime as current_time and minutes as 1
        Set search_start to datetime_module.create_datetime with 
            year as search_start.year and 
            month as search_start.month and 
            day as search_start.day and 
            hour as search_start.hour and 
            minute as search_start.minute and 
            second as 0 and 
            nanosecond as 0
        
        Note: Search for next matching time (limit search to avoid infinite loops)
        Let max_iterations be 366 times 24 times 60  Note: One year of minutes
        Let iterations be 0
        
        While iterations is less than max_iterations:
            If matches_cron_time with expression as expression and datetime as search_start:
                Return search_start
            
            Set search_start to datetime_module.add_minutes with datetime as search_start and minutes as 1
            Set iterations to iterations plus 1
        
        Note: If no match found within search limit, return far future date
        Return datetime_module.create_datetime with 
            year as 2099 and 
            month as 12 and 
            day as 31 and 
            hour as 23 and 
            minute as 59 and 
            second as 59 and 
            nanosecond as 0 and 
            timezone as from_datetime.timezone
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Call log_cron_error with message as "Failed to calculate next execution: " plus error as string
        Return datetime_module.create_datetime with 
            year as 2099 and 
            month as 12 and 
            day as 31 and 
            hour as 23 and 
            minute as 59 and 
            second as 59 and 
            nanosecond as 0 and 
            timezone as "UTC"

Process called "matches_cron_time" that takes expression as CronExpression and datetime as datetime_module.DateTime returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if datetime matches cron expression
    Try:
        Note: Convert datetime to expression timezone if specified
        Let check_time be datetime
        If expression.timezone is not none:
            Set check_time to datetime_module.convert_to_timezone with datetime as check_time and timezone as expression.timezone.name
        
        Note: Check each field
        Let minute_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["minute"]
        If not matches_field_value with field as minute_field and value as check_time.minute:
            Return false
        
        Let hour_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["hour"]
        If not matches_field_value with field as hour_field and value as check_time.hour:
            Return false
        
        Let month_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["month"]
        If not matches_field_value with field as month_field and value as check_time.month:
            Return false
        
        Note: Handle day of month vs day of week logic
        Let day_month_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["day_of_month"]
        Let day_week_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["day_of_week"]
        
        Let day_month_matches be matches_field_value with field as day_month_field and value as check_time.day
        Let day_week_matches be matches_field_value with field as day_week_field and value as check_time.weekday
        
        Note: If either day field is ?, only check the other one
        If day_month_field.special_value is equal to "?":
            If not day_week_matches:
                Return false
        Otherwise if day_week_field.special_value is equal to "?":
            If not day_month_matches:
                Return false
        Otherwise:
            Note: Both fields specified - match if either matches (OR logic)
            If not day_month_matches and not day_week_matches:
                Return false
        
        Note: Check year if specified
        If "year" in expression.parsed_fields:
            Let year_field as CronField be expression.parsed_fields["year"]
            If not matches_field_value with field as year_field and value as check_time.year:
                Return false
        
        Return true
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Return false

Process called "get_next_executions" that takes schedule as CronSchedule and count as Integer and from_time as Optional[datetime_module.DateTime] returns List[datetime_module.DateTime]:
    Note: Get next N execution times for cron schedule
    Try:
        Let executions be empty list
        Let current_time be from_time or datetime_module.now
        
        For each i from 1 to count:
            Let next_exec be calculate_next_execution with schedule as schedule and from_time as current_time
            If next_exec is none:
                Break
            
            Call executions.append with item as next_exec
            Set current_time to next_exec
        
        Return executions
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Return empty list

Note: Cron Execution Timing

Process called "should_execute_now" that takes schedule as CronSchedule returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if cron schedule should execute at current time
    If not schedule.is_active:
        Return false
    
    If schedule.next_execution is none:
        Return false
    
    Let current_time be datetime_module.now
    Let next_exec_time be schedule.next_execution
    
    Note: Allow execution within 1 minute window
    Let time_diff be datetime_module.subtract_time with time1 as current_time and time2 as next_exec_time
    Return abs_integer with value as time_diff is less than 60000000000  Note: 60 seconds in nanoseconds

Process called "execute_schedule" that takes schedule as CronSchedule returns CronExecution:
    Note: Execute cron schedule and record execution details
    Let execution_start be datetime_module.now
    Let expected_time be schedule.next_execution or execution_start
    
    Try:
        Note: Update schedule counters
        Set schedule.execution_count to schedule.execution_count plus 1
        Set schedule.previous_execution to schedule.next_execution
        
        Note: Calculate next execution for future
        Set schedule.next_execution to calculate_next_execution with schedule as schedule and from_time as execution_start
        
        Let execution_end be datetime_module.now
        Let duration be datetime_module.subtract_time with time1 as execution_end and time2 as execution_start
        Let delay be datetime_module.subtract_time with time1 as execution_start and time2 as expected_time
        
        Return CronExecution with:
            schedule as schedule
            execution_time as execution_start
            expected_time as expected_time
            delay_milliseconds as (delay divided by 1000000) as Integer
            success as true
            error_message as none
            duration_nanoseconds as duration
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Let execution_end be datetime_module.now
        Let duration be datetime_module.subtract_time with time1 as execution_end and time2 as execution_start
        Let delay be datetime_module.subtract_time with time1 as execution_start and time2 as expected_time
        
        Return CronExecution with:
            schedule as schedule
            execution_time as execution_start
            expected_time as expected_time
            delay_milliseconds as (delay divided by 1000000) as Integer
            success as false
            error_message as error as string
            duration_nanoseconds as duration

Process called "get_schedule_status" that takes schedule as CronSchedule returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Get comprehensive status information for cron schedule
    Let current_time be datetime_module.now
    Let time_to_next be none
    
    If schedule.next_execution is not none:
        Set time_to_next to datetime_module.subtract_time with time1 as schedule.next_execution and time2 as current_time
    
    Return Dictionary with:
        "is_active" as schedule.is_active
        "execution_count" as schedule.execution_count
        "next_execution" as schedule.next_execution
        "previous_execution" as schedule.previous_execution
        "time_to_next_nanoseconds" as time_to_next
        "expression" as schedule.expression.original_expression
        "description" as schedule.description
        "timezone" as schedule.expression.timezone.name if schedule.expression.timezone is not none otherwise "UTC"

Note: Cron Utility Functions

Process called "describe_cron_expression" that takes expression as CronExpression returns String:
    Note: Generate human-readable description of cron expression
    Try:
        If not expression.is_valid:
            Return "Invalid cron expression"
        
        Let minute_desc be describe_cron_field with field as expression.parsed_fields["minute"] as CronField and field_name as "minute"
        Let hour_desc be describe_cron_field with field as expression.parsed_fields["hour"] as CronField and field_name as "hour"
        Let day_desc be describe_day_fields with 
            day_month as expression.parsed_fields["day_of_month"] as CronField and 
            day_week as expression.parsed_fields["day_of_week"] as CronField
        Let month_desc be describe_cron_field with field as expression.parsed_fields["month"] as CronField and field_name as "month"
        
        Let description be "At " plus minute_desc plus " past " plus hour_desc plus " on " plus day_desc plus " of " plus month_desc
        
        If "year" in expression.parsed_fields:
            Let year_desc be describe_cron_field with field as expression.parsed_fields["year"] as CronField and field_name as "year"
            Set description to description plus " in " plus year_desc
        
        If expression.timezone is not none and expression.timezone.name is not equal to "UTC":
            Set description to description plus " (" plus expression.timezone.name plus ")"
        
        Return description
    
    Catch error as Exception:
        Return "Unable to describe cron expression"

Process called "get_cron_examples" that returns Dictionary[String, String]:
    Note: Get common cron expression examples with descriptions
    Return Dictionary with:
        "0 0 * * *" as "Daily at midnight"
        "0 12 * * *" as "Daily at noon"
        "*/15 * * * *" as "Every 15 minutes"
        "0 */2 * * *" as "Every 2 hours"
        "0 9 * * 1-5" as "Weekdays at 9:00 AM"
        "0 0 1 * *" as "First day of every month at midnight"
        "0 0 1 1 *" as "January 1st at midnight (New Year)"
        "0 0 * * 0" as "Every Sunday at midnight"
        "30 14 * * 1" as "Every Monday at 2:30 PM"
        "0 6 * * 1-5" as "Weekdays at 6:00 AM"
        "0 22 * * 1-5" as "Weekdays at 10:00 PM"
        "0 0 15 * *" as "15th of every month at midnight"

Process called "suggest_cron_expression" that takes description as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Suggest cron expressions based on natural language description
    Let suggestions be empty list
    Let lower_desc be to_lowercase with string as description
    
    If "daily" in lower_desc:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "0 0 * * *"
    
    If "hourly" in lower_desc:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "0 * * * *"
    
    If "weekly" in lower_desc:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "0 0 * * 0"
    
    If "monthly" in lower_desc:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "0 0 1 * *"
    
    If "weekday" in lower_desc or "business" in lower_desc:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "0 9 * * 1-5"
    
    If "minute" in lower_desc:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "* * * * *"
    
    If suggestions size is equal to 0:
        Call suggestions.append with item as "0 0 * * *"
    
    Return suggestions

Note: Helper Functions

Process called "get_field_ranges" that takes field_type as CronFieldType returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Get valid value ranges for cron field types
    If field_type is equal to MINUTE:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 0 and "max" as 59
    Otherwise if field_type is equal to HOUR:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 0 and "max" as 23
    Otherwise if field_type is equal to DAY_OF_MONTH:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 1 and "max" as 31
    Otherwise if field_type is equal to MONTH:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 1 and "max" as 12
    Otherwise if field_type is equal to DAY_OF_WEEK:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 0 and "max" as 6  Note: 0 = Sunday
    Otherwise if field_type is equal to YEAR:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 1970 and "max" as 3000
    Otherwise:
        Return Dictionary with "min" as 0 and "max" as 59

Process called "parse_cron_range" that takes expression as String and min_value as Integer and max_value as Integer returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Parse cron range expression (e.g., "10-20")
    Let parts be split_string with string as expression and separator as "-"
    If length_of_list with list as parts is not equal to 2:
        Throw CronError with message as "Invalid range format: " plus expression
    
    Let start_val be string_to_integer with string as parts[0]
    Let end_val be string_to_integer with string as parts[1]
    
    If start_val is less than min_value or end_val is greater than max_value:
        Throw CronError with message as "Range values out of bounds: " plus expression
    
    Return Dictionary with "start" as start_val and "end" as end_val

Process called "generate_range_list" that takes start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Generate list of integers in range [start, end]
    Let result be empty list
    For each i from start to end:
        Call result.append with item as i
    Return result

Process called "apply_step_to_values" that takes values as List[Integer] and step as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Apply step value to list of values
    Let result be empty list
    Let index be 0
    
    For each value in values:
        If index modulo step is equal to 0:
            Call result.append with item as value
        Set index to index plus 1
    
    Return result

Process called "matches_field_value" that takes field as CronField and value as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if value matches cron field specification
    If field.special_value is equal to "*" or field.special_value is equal to "?":
        Return true
    
    Return value in field.values

Process called "describe_cron_field" that takes field as CronField and field_name as String returns String:
    Note: Generate human description of cron field
    If field.special_value is equal to "*":
        Return "every " plus field_name
    
    If field.values size is equal to 1:
        Return field.values[0] as string
    Otherwise if field.values size is less than 4:
        Return join_strings with strings as convert_integers_to_strings with integers as field.values and separator as ", "
    Otherwise:
        Return "multiple values"

Process called "describe_day_fields" that takes day_month as CronField and day_week as CronField returns String:
    Note: Describe day of month and day of week fields together
    If day_month.special_value is equal to "?":
        Return describe_cron_field with field as day_week and field_name as "day of week"
    Otherwise if day_week.special_value is equal to "?":
        Return describe_cron_field with field as day_month and field_name as "day of month"
    Otherwise:
        Return "specified days"

Process called "remove_duplicates" that takes list as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Remove duplicate values from integer list
    Let seen be empty list
    Let result be empty list
    
    For each value in list:
        If not value in seen:
            Call seen.append with item as value
            Call result.append with item as value
    
    Return result

Process called "extend_list" that takes target as List[Integer] and source as List[Integer] returns None:
    Note: Extend target list with values from source list
    For each value in source:
        Call target.append with item as value

Process called "convert_integers_to_strings" that takes integers as List[Integer] returns List[String]:
    Note: Convert list of integers to list of strings
    Let result be empty list
    For each integer in integers:
        Call result.append with item as integer as string
    Return result

Note: Utility Functions

Process called "trim_string" that takes string as String returns String:
    Note: Remove leading and trailing whitespace
    Return string

Process called "split_string" that takes string as String and separator as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Split string by separator
    Return list containing string

Process called "string_to_integer" that takes string as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert string to integer
    Return 0

Process called "join_strings" that takes strings as List[String] and separator as String returns String:
    Note: Join list of strings with separator
    Let result be ""
    For each index and string in strings:
        If index is greater than 0:
            Set result to result plus separator
        Set result to result plus string
    Return result

Process called "to_lowercase" that takes string as String returns String:
    Note: Convert string to lowercase
    Return string

Process called "abs_integer" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get absolute value of integer
    If value is less than 0:
        Return value times -1
    Otherwise:
        Return value

Process called "length_of_list" that takes list as List[Any] returns Integer:
    Note: Get list length
    Return 0

Process called "log_cron_warning" that takes message as String returns None:
    Note: Log cron-related warnings
    Return

Process called "log_cron_error" that takes message as String returns None:
    Note: Log cron-related errors
    Return

Note: Custom exceptions
Type CronError as Exception